Finding tour companies featuring Halong Bay in Hanoi is easy. However, knowing which one to trust is more tricky. I can't say we did well. The day we booked, it seems, they didn't have many people, so they put us on a smaller and older boat. Rather untidy and food was bad. Best sea food available all around and they served lousy fried crap. We questioned the tour guide about the boat and he assured us that we were on the correct one. It wasn't. So, be careful who you book with and it probably is worth it to go for a better, even more expensive, one. Nonetheless, it still was amazing. Just seeing the bay was worthy of the time and effort. Must see it.
Written August 25, 2011
JenInMontreal
Ferney-Voltaire95 contributions
Excursion of a Lifetime
Aug 2011
We did the 2-day/1-night cruise, which was just the right amount of time. We booked through Handspan Travel Agency in Hanoi Old Quarter, just two days in advance. Handspan is reputedly more ecofriendly than most agencies. Their transfer operation was smooth and comfortable. The drive to Halong City took 3 and a half hours, 4 hours return.
Having heard the reports of two separate tourist junks sinking in Halong Bay with considerable loss of life in the last year, we were a bit wary, but were soon reassured by the good reputation of the company as well as by the serious safety briefing at the start of our cruise. It is clear just by looking at the vessel that it is perfectly sturdy and seaworthy, with a no-nonsense crew .
We had a double cabin with two twin beds that they put together to make one bed just large enough for us and our 5-year-old to sleep comfortably. We loved lying in bed watching the breathtaking scenery float by the wall-to-wall windows. The bathroom and shower are sparkling with plentiful hot water. There is also a safe, bathrobes and flipflops, as well as safety equipment such as a flashlight and a large mallet to break the windows if the ship sinks. There is a panic buttons outside each cabin door.
The cabin and common areas were well airconditioned.
For an outfit with a captive audience, they definitely don't skimp on the food. Drinks are not included, but aren't as much of a gouge as you might expect.
Activities: We stopped at a beach near Titop that was tiny, but scenic and livened up by Vietnamese daytrippers who gave us the brief illusion that we weren't on the tourist trail. Towels and chilled bottles of water are handed out as you get off the tender boat. In the evening, we were taken by rowboat to see one of the floating villages, and we enjoyed peering into people's open windows and doors to see how they live and work. The other option was an hour of kayaking for an extra $10. While the top deck of the junk is scorching during the day, it cools off nicely after dusk, and we lounged on the deckchairs (of which there are many) sipping wine. We opted out of the cave visit the next morning, choosing instead to laze around alternately in bed and on deck.
Breakfast was very good. When our guide, Mr. T, was informed by our daughter that it was her birthday, he had a giant melon carved up into a flower design and presented it to her at our table, with everyone singing 'Happy Birthday', a very nice surprise indeed!
Note that they only put the sails up, for show, in the morning.
This really is the best way to see Halong Bay.
Written August 22, 2011
Ombudsmannen
Helsinki, Finland84 contributions
Nice experience
Jun 2011
There is no option Family, or Family with adult children, I have to choose Family with teenagers. On our 22 days tour around Vietnam we took a one night/two days cruise on Ha Long Bay. The operator was Indochina Junk, our vessel was Lagoon Explorer. We were five adults and we had the whole ship to ourselves, with a 5 member crew. The interior was quite nice, there was 5 air conditioned cabins + a dining room inside, and a large open deck with a covered dining area and sundeck with chairs. The first day we lunch while cruising in the magnificent Bai Tu Long Bay, admiring the fascinating rock formations. Later we enjoyed swimming in the crystal clear water., explored the secluded Thien Canh Son Cave. Had a short cruise to Hon Co Island where we relaxed on a white sandy beach, swimming and took a kayak tour. In the evening we had a nice dinner and stay overnight on board. Following morning we enjoy the bay‚Äôs morning landscape while we had breakfast in the open air. After breakfast we visited Vung Vieng fishing village in a rustic rowing-boat, met the local people and pass through the floating school and fish farms. It was very fascinating to see how the fishermen live with their families. Then we had some more leisure time for swimming in the middle of the bay. Later we cruised back to Ha Long Bay harbour while we enjoyed a good lunch.
Most annoying was the overpriced beer, drinks and wine on board. A can of beer cost 8000 VND in the local supermarket, on board they charge 50.000 VND for a beer. It's only 1,65 ‚Ç¨ for a can but if compared to the local prices it's a robbery. Drinks and wines charged in the same way. Our bill for drinks and wine we had on board was 85 ‚Ç¨ witch is a a lot considering Vietnam general price levels. Because of the feeling being ripped off we had no positive feelings about tipping the crew. Otherwise we were very pleased.
Our whole Vietnam tour, including all hotel stays, car with guide and driver + all attractions, was arranged by Vivu Travel from Hanoi. Their service was first class and prices very competitive. I recommend Vivu Travel warmly. The same owner has also an other agency, KT Adventures, they can arrange all kind of tours and activities for you.
Written August 21, 2011
Becca_G8
Santa Barbara, CA79 contributions
Huong Hai Junk, nice trip, great guide.
We took a 2 night cruise with Huong Hai Junk. We liked the boat, just the right size (has five double rooms-small but nice). the boat has three levels, the lower level is the bedrooms, second level is the restaurant, the top level is a sun/viewing deck.
Day one was disappointing, we did not like the trip to the cave, very crowded with tourists, and if you have been to limestone caves before it is not that interesting. Two of us kayaked, which was fun. at night all boats are required to anchor in one bay, which was okay, but a bit smelly (all engines running). Day two was great, we were able to get further out to see fabulous views, and went on a great kayak trip to a beach. Virtually no other tourists were seen. Our guide was great, lots of great discussions about the area and his life. The last morning we took a smaller boat through a tunnel into a lagoon where monkeys can be seen. Unfortunately the monkeys are fed by the guides and tourists, so they are not really wild. The lagoon was dirty and crowded with tourists, not worthwhile. the takeaway message is don't bother with a one night tour if you want to see really beautiful and pristine views.
The food was overly plentiful (9 or 10 dishes). It was fresh and okay, but too many fried dishes. All beverages are charged as extra, including water. You are also charged if you bring your own wine, so there is no way around it.
